''Midwinter'' was covered by [[Eurogamer]]'s Dan Whitehead in a retrospective article, which praised the mix of genres the game contained, calling it "a unique creature; a priceless transitional specimen in the fossil record of gaming."<ref>{{cite web|last=Whitehead |first=Dan |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2010-12-18-retrospective-midwinter-article |title=Retrospective: Midwinter Article - Retro - Page 1 |publisher=Eurogamer.net |date=2010-12-19 |accessdate=2013-11-16}}</ref> In their 2009 retrospective article, ''[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]]'' staff wrote: "Playing it felt like time travel – a sneak peak at the blueprint that showed how games were going to be. It was then, and is now, an enormous accomplishment."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.next-gen.biz/features/time-extend-midwinter |title=Time Extend: Midwinter |publisher=Next-gen.biz |date= |accessdate=2013-11-16 |url-status=live |archive-date=2012-05-18 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120518113258/http://www.edge-online.com/features/time-extend-midwinter}}</ref> [[GameSpot]] featured ''Midwinter'' in its feature article "Unsung Heroes" about the 10 games most deserving "more recognition than they received" and should be "remembered for their contributions to their respective genres and to gaming as a whole."<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.gamespot.com/gamespot/features/pc/unsung_heroes/sec2_10.html |title=Unsung Heroes: Ground Breaking Games – Midwinter|last=Baker|first=T. Byrl|publisher=GameSpot |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100707141052/http://www.gamespot.com/gamespot/features/pc/unsung_heroes/sec2_10.html |archivedate=2010-07-07 |accessdate=2014-10-30}}</ref>

