==Legacy==
An indirect sequel titled ''[[Flames of Freedom]]'', also known as ''Midwinter II: Flames of Freedom'' or ''Midwinter 2'', was developed by Maelstrom Games and published by [[MicroProse]] for the same platforms in 1991. In 2014, Chilli Hugger Software announced a ''Midwinter'' remake project;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2014-01-09-wintry-survival-sim-midwinter-is-getting-a-remake-in-2015|title=Wintry survival sim Midwinter is getting a remake in 2015|last=Matulef|first=Jeffrey|date=9 January 2014|work=[[Eurogamer]]|publisher=Gamer Network|accessdate=9 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.themidwinterreport.com/press_release_1/|title=Chilli Hugger Software to remake Mike Singleton's Midwinter 16-bit classic will be updated for PC and consoles|last=Wild|first=Chris|date=9 January 2014|work=The Midwinter Report|accessdate=9 January 2014|archive-date=9 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140109193559/http://blog.themidwinterreport.com/press_release_1/|url-status=dead}}</ref> originally planned for a 2015 release, the remake has been indefinitely delayed and possibly abandoned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kotaku.com.au/2016/05/2015-release-of-midwinter-remake-is-just-a-tad-bit-late/|title=The 2015 Release of the Midwinter Remake is a Tad on the Late Side|date=29 May 2016}}</ref>

